  "prompt": "Why the colour of wires in homes are black, green and red?",
  "response": "The colors of electrical wires in homes serve specific purposes for safety and identification:\n\n1. Black Wire:\n- Typically carries the \"hot\" or live electrical current\n- Responsible for supplying power to electrical devices\n- Carries the primary electrical load\n\n2. Green Wire:\n- Used as a ground wire\n- Provides a safe path for electrical current in case of a fault\n- Helps prevent electrical shocks and protects against potential equipment damage\n- Connects electrical systems to the earth ground\n\n3. Red Wire:\n- Often used as a secondary \"hot\" wire\n- Common in 220-240 volt circuits\n- Used in certain switched circuits or three-way switch configurations\n- Can also indicate a specific circuit or connection\n\nNote that wire color standards can vary slightly between countries:\n- United States: Black, red, and green are standard\n- United Kingdom: Brown (live), blue (neutral), and green/yellow (ground)\n- European countries: Brown, blue, and green/yellow\n\nThese color conventions help electricians and homeowners quickly identify wire functions and ensure safe electrical installations. Always consult a professional electrician for specific electrical work.",
